<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="observations">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Observations.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
This species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Halling, R" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="379 - 385" refId="B11" refString="Halling, R, 1993. Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America. Mycotaxon 47: 379 - 385" title="Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America." volume="47" year="1993">Halling (1993)</bibRefCitation>
from Bolivian specimens. It is characterized by its relatively large, bright orange basidiomes, covered with scattered dextrinoid setiform hairs. The most similar species is 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. mayarum" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="mayarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. mayarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which shares morphological characters such as the large basidiomes with bright orange coloration. These two species, however, differ clearly by the smaller spores and by the presence of ornamented cheilocystidia in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. mayarum" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="mayarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. mayarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Another similar species is 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. aurantiaca" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from American Samoa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5248/120.493" author="Kropp, BR" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="493 - 503" refId="B17" refString="Kropp, BR, Albee-Scott, S, 2012. Moniliophthora aurantiaca sp. nov., a Polynesian species occurring in littoral forest. Mycotaxon 120: 493 - 503, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5248/120.493" title="Moniliophthora aurantiaca sp. nov., a Polynesian species occurring in littoral forest." url="https://doi.org/10.5248/120.493" volume="120" year="2012">Kropp and Albee-Scott 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Both share the orange colored pileus surface with a narrow light yellowish margin. However, they differ in that 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. aurantiaca" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the smaller pileus (3-15 mm broad), smaller basidiospores (7.5-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) and numerous cheilocystidia with several irregular apical appendages resembling fingers (Kroop and Albee-Scott 2012). Another similar species is 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. hygrocybioides" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="hygrocybioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. hygrocybioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Henn.) Singer from Africa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.2537" author="Singer, R" journalOrPublisher="Fieldiana, Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 133" refId="B30" refString="Singer, R, 1989. New taxa and new combinations of Agaricales (Diagnoses fungorum novorum agaricalium IV). Fieldiana, Botany 21: 1 - 133, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.2537" title="New taxa and new combinations of Agaricales (Diagnoses fungorum novorum agaricalium IV)." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.2537" volume="21" year="1989">Singer 1989</bibRefCitation>
), however this is a smaller fungus (pileus 6-11 mm broad) with an umbilicate to papilate pileus that is pilose at the margin (
<bibRefCitation author="Halling, R" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="379 - 385" refId="B11" refString="Halling, R, 1993. Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America. Mycotaxon 47: 379 - 385" title="Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America." volume="47" year="1993">Halling 1993</bibRefCitation>
). Based on its morphological characters such as the bright orange pileus surface, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. hygrociboides" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="hygrociboides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. hygrociboides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be included in the genus 
<taxonomicName genus="Moniliphthora" lsidName="Moniliphthora" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Moniliphthora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but new collections are needed to elucidate its habitat and to obtain sequences and corroborate this hypothesis (currently there are not sequences available for 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. hygrocybioides" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="hygrocybioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. hygrocybioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
Other known parasitic Neotropical species are 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. perniciosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="perniciosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. perniciosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. trinitatis" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="trinitatis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. trinitatis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dennis and 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. siparunae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="siparunae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. siparunae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Singer. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aime &amp; Phillips-Mora" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Stahel" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Moniliophthora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Moniliophthora perniciosa" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="perniciosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Moniliophthora perniciosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a destructive parasite of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Theobroma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Theobroma cacao" order="Malvales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cacao">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Theobroma cacao</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, differs in having smaller basidiomes (pileus up to 25 mm diam) with a red pileus surface and white stipe (
<bibRefCitation author="Singer, R" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 347" refId="B29" refString="Singer, R, 1976. Marasmieae (Basidiomycetes - Tricholomataceae). Flora Neotropica 17: 1 - 347" title="Marasmieae (Basidiomycetes - Tricholomataceae)." volume="17" year="1976">Singer 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/mycologia.97.5.1012" author="Aime, MC" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="1012 - 1022" refId="B1" refString="Aime, MC, Phillips-Mora, W, 2005. The causal agents of witches' broom and frosty pod rot of cacao (chocolate, Theobroma cacao) form a new lineage of Marasmiaceae. Mycologia 97: 1012 - 1022, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/mycologia.97.5.1012" title="The causal agents of witches' broom and frosty pod rot of cacao (chocolate, Theobroma cacao) form a new lineage of Marasmiaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/mycologia.97.5.1012" volume="97" year="2005">Aime and Phillips-Mora 2005</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dennis" authorityYear="1970" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Crinipellis trinitatis" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="trinitatis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Crinipellis trinitatis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a smaller, red pileus and smaller spores [5-7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
ss. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(51)80030-5" author="Dennis, RWG" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the British Mycological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="411 - 482" refId="B6" refString="Dennis, RWG, 1951. Some Agaricaceae from Trinidad and Venezuela. Leucosporae: Part 1. Transactions of the British Mycological Society 34: 411 - 482, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(51)80030-5" title="Some Agaricaceae from Trinidad and Venezuela. Leucosporae: Part 1." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(51)80030-5" volume="34" year="1951">Dennis (1951)</bibRefCitation>
and 7-9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
ss. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pegler, DN" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin Additional Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 668" refId="B23" refString="Pegler, DN, 1983. Agaric Flora of the Lesser Antilles. Kew Bulletin Additional Series 9: 1 - 668" title="Agaric Flora of the Lesser Antilles." volume="9" year="1983">Pegler (1983)</bibRefCitation>
].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Singer" authorityYear="1943" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Crinipellis siparunae" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="siparunae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Crinipellis siparunae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widely distributed species that is microscopically similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. ticoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="ticoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. ticoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially regarding the range of spore size. However, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. siparunae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="siparunae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. siparunae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by its lilac to brownish lilac pileus surface and by its appendiculate cheilocystidia (
<bibRefCitation author="Singer, R" journalOrPublisher="Lilloa" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="441 - 533" refId="B28" refString="Singer, R, 1942. A monographic study of the genera Crinipellis and Chaetocalathus. Lilloa 8: 441 - 533" title="A monographic study of the genera Crinipellis and Chaetocalathus." volume="8" year="1942">Singer 1942</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Singer, R" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 347" refId="B29" refString="Singer, R, 1976. Marasmieae (Basidiomycetes - Tricholomataceae). Flora Neotropica 17: 1 - 347" title="Marasmieae (Basidiomycetes - Tricholomataceae)." volume="17" year="1976">1976</bibRefCitation>
). A taxon thought to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. siparunae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="siparunae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. siparunae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. eggersii subsp. var. var. lilaciceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="variety" species="eggersii" subSpecies="var." variety="lilaciceps">C. eggersii Pat. var. lilaciceps</taxonomicName>
Singer and described from Amazonian Ecuador shares unornamented cheilocystidia with 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. ticoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="ticoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">C. ticoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs from the latter in having a violet to lilac vs orange pileus, and broader basidiospores 6-6.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(3.8-)4.5-6.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Singer, R" journalOrPublisher="Flora Neotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 347" refId="B29" refString="Singer, R, 1976. Marasmieae (Basidiomycetes - Tricholomataceae). Flora Neotropica 17: 1 - 347" title="Marasmieae (Basidiomycetes - Tricholomataceae)." volume="17" year="1976">Singer 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kerekes, JF" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="101 - 151" refId="B13" refString="Kerekes, JF, Desjardin, DE, 2009. A monograph of the genera Crinipellis and Moniliophthora from Southeast Asia including molecular phylogeny of the nrITS region. Fungal Diversity 37: 101 - 151" title="A monograph of the genera Crinipellis and Moniliophthora from Southeast Asia including molecular phylogeny of the nrITS region." volume="37" year="2009">Kerekes and Desjardin 2009</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="var. eggersii" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Crinipellis eggersii subsp. var. var. eggersii" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="variety" species="eggersii" subSpecies="var." variety="eggersii">Crinipellis eggersii var. eggersii</taxonomicName>
, which includes the facultative synonym 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Marasmius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Marasmius vinosus" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="vinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Marasmius vinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Speg. described from Argentina, has similar spore dimensions (mostly 11-13 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.5-6.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) but differs in having a purple to violet purple pileus and a variety of cheilocystidia shapes (ampullaceous, fusiform, cylindrical or clavate and mostly forked, obtuse or mucronate, sometimes with a subcapitate or capitate apex).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
Of the three recent collections in northern Argentina, the specimens of the Yungas forest (Niveiro et al. 2249) closely resemble the original description of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. ticoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="ticoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">M. ticoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with specimens not exceeding 40 mm broad and having a bright red pileus surface (
<bibRefCitation author="Halling, R" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="379 - 385" refId="B11" refString="Halling, R, 1993. Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America. Mycotaxon 47: 379 - 385" title="Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America." volume="47" year="1993">Halling 1993</bibRefCitation>
). However, the specimens of the Chaco region differ in having larger basidiomes up to 60 mm broad, and a paler coloration (orange with a yellowish margin), differences that may be due to the drier weather conditions in the Chaco region. Another important difference observed in the Argentinean specimens is the habitat. 
<bibRefCitation author="Halling, R" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="379 - 385" refId="B11" refString="Halling, R, 1993. Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America. Mycotaxon 47: 379 - 385" title="Two new Crinipellinae (Tricholomataceae: Marasmiae) from South America." volume="47" year="1993">Halling (1993)</bibRefCitation>
found this species growing on rotten wood, however, the new specimens examined were growing on tree trunks and roots of living trees, confirming a biotrophic habit for this species during at least part of its life history.
</paragraph>
